1 h. One representative of the national park service, appointed by the national park
2 service; and
3 i. One representative of the Indian affairs commission, appointed by the governor.
4 2. The working group shall:
5 a. In cooperation with the national park service and the United States government,
6 provide recommendations for managing the population of wild horses in the
7 Theodore Roosevelt national park to remain above two hundred horses;
8 b. Identify and offer opportunities to support and maintain the wild horses within the
9 Theodore Roosevelt national park;
10 c. Promote the wild horses to benefit tourism and to make recommendations to the
11 department;
12 d. Assist the department in carrying out activities to educate the public;
13 e. Meet quarterly; and
14 f. Provide, by July first of each year, a report to the legislative management which
15 includes the working group's detailed plan to implement the requirements of this
16 section.
17 3. The working group may make recommendations for management activities, including
18 birth control, removals, and permanent placement of horses after removal. All
19 management activities must be humane and nonlethal.
20 4. The working group may enter an agreement with the national park service to
21 implement this section.
22 5. Upon recommendation from the working group, the state may enter an agreement with
23 a private entity to address any issues related to the wild horses in the Theodore
24 Roosevelt national park.
25 SECTION 2. APPROPRIATION - DEPARTMENT OF COMMERCE - THEODORE
26 ROOSEVELT NATIONAL PARK WORKING GROUP. There is appropriated out of any moneys
27 in the general fund in the state treasury, not otherwise appropriated, the sum of $50,000, or so
28 much of the sum as may be necessary, to the department of commerce for the purpose of
29 administering the Theodore Roosevelt national park working group, for the biennium beginning
30 July 1, 2025, and ending June 30, 2027.
